{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4f7262c1-cd73-4a76-9df5-b243e0b431b8","content":"`dotnet-dump` is available. To analyze your dump, here's what to do:\n\n**1. Start an interactive analysis session:**\n```bash\ndotnet-dump analyze /path/to/your-file.dmp\n```\n\n**2. Useful SOS commands inside the session:**\n\n| Command | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `clrstack` | Managed call stack of current thread |\n| `pe` (PrintException) | Show the last exception |\n| `clrthreads` | List all managed threads |\n| `setthread <id>` | Switch to a specific thread |\n| `dso` (DumpStackObjects) | Objects on the stack |\n| `dumpheap -stat` | Heap summary |\n| `exit` | Quit |\n\n**Quick triage flow:** Start with `pe` to check for an unhandled exception, then `clrthreads` to find threads with exceptions, and `clrstack` to see the call stack.\n\nWould you like me to run `dotnet-dump analyze` on your file? If so, please share the path to the `.dmp` file.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"34973793-4af3-4953-9add-aaeedc4ecdc6","outputTokens":262,"requestId":"D800:1F45CF:D794EB:F914EC:69F2B6FC"},"id":"586e29ec-0fd5-485c-bf3b-566cad1ee0b1","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:57:24.981Z","parentId":"02f24a9c-59f5-4e48-8151-4af60b5152e7"}
